<ReaderLayout
  title="Systems That Break Interestingly"
  description="How things fail, why that's useful, and what we can learn from broken systems."
  updated="February 2026"
  tags={['systems', 'failure', 'complexity', 'architecture']}
>
  <p>
    I'm obsessed with systems that fail in interesting ways. Not catastrophic failures
    that ruin people's days, but elegant failures that reveal something fundamental
    about how complex systems work.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "A complex system that works is invariably found to have evolved from a simple
    system that worked. A complex system designed from scratch never works."
    <br />— John Gall
  </blockquote>

  <h2>The Paradox of Success</h2>

  <p>
    The most interesting failures happen in systems that were working perfectly.
    Success breeds complexity, complexity breeds failure, failure breeds...
    well, that's where it gets interesting.
  </p>

  <h2>📖 Case Studies</h2>

  <h3>The 1999 Mars Climate Orbiter</h3>
  <p>
    One team used metric units. Another used imperial. The orbiter burned up in the
    atmosphere. $193 million lesson in the importance of shared assumptions.
  </p>

  <h3>Therac-25 Radiation Machine</h3>
  <p>
    A race condition in software caused lethal radiation overdoses. Six patients died.
    This is the canonical case study in why you can't trust software with safety.
  </p>

  <h3>Knight Capital's $440 Million Bug</h3>
  <p>
    A deployment script with a single flag set wrong erased $440 million in 45 minutes.
    The company nearly went bankrupt. Now every deploy process includes this story.
  </p>

  <h2>🧠 Mental Models</h2>

  <h3>Cascade vs. Parallel</h3>
  <p>
    When one failure triggers another, you get cascades (think: electrical grid).
    When failures are independent, you get parallel failures (think: multiple servers).
    Parallel is better. Contained is better.
  </p>

  <h3>The Turkey Problem</h3>
  <p>
    A turkey is fed every day for 1000 days. Each day, the probability of being fed
    goes up. On day 1001, it's Thanksgiving. The turkey's confidence interval was
    wrong. Never trust a system just because it's been consistent.
  </p>

  <h3>Hyrum's Law</h3>
  <p>
    "With a sufficient number of users of an API, it does not matter what you promise
    in the contract: all observable behaviors of your system will be depended on by
    somebody."
  </p>

  <h2>🔧 Designing for Failure</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Chaos Engineering</strong> - Netflix's approach of actively breaking things in production</li>
    <li><strong>Circuit Breakers</strong> - Preventing cascade failures by failing fast</li>
    <li><strong>Idempotency</strong> - Doing the same thing twice has the same effect as once</li>
    <li><strong>Feature Flags</strong> - Turning things off is as important as turning them on</li>
    <li><strong>Observability</strong> - You can't fix what you can't see</li>
  </ul>

